@node "ToolTypes" "ToolTypes"

    @{b}SUPPORTED PROGRAM-TOOLTYPES@{ub}

    @{b}New:@{ub}

    ñ @{fg shine}HOLD@{fg text}


    @{b}ToolTypes:@{ub}

    ñ @{fg shine}HOLD@{fg text}
                               If you specify this tooltype, after end of the
                               simulate mode your settings will be taken over
                               to normal program run. This can be useful if you
                               want to change more than one setting at once.
                               DEFAULT: (HOLD)

    ñ @{fg shine}QUICKRESET@{fg text}
                               Here you can define sort of a 'panic button'.
                               You define an 'Input Description String' like
                               "space", "f1", "return", "delete", "help",
                               "diskinserted"
                               DEFAULT: (QUICKRESET=)

    ñ @{fg shine}FREQWARN@{fg text}
                               If you limit the editable frequencies thru the
                               tooltypes MIN_HZ, MAX_HZ, MIN_KHZ and MAX KHZ,
                               this tooltype, if specified, gives you a warning,
                               if the start frequencies are already out of range.
                               DEFAULT: (FREQWARN)

    ñ @{fg shine}OLDHZ@{fg text}
                               Screenmode-compatible calculation of Hz/kHz values.
                               Not recommended. Inaccurate
                               WARNING: MIN_HZ, MAX_HZ, MIN_KHZ, MAX_KHZ
                                        are inaccurate, too !
                               DEFAULT: (OLDHZ)

    ñ @{fg shine}BIGVIRTUAL@{fg text}
                               All groups of the window are placed in one big
                               virtual group.
                               DEFAULT: (BIGVIRTUAL)

    ñ @{fg shine}VIRTGROUPS@{fg text}
                               Every settings group is in a virtual group and
                               the information group is in a virtual group.
                               DEFAULT: (VIRTGROUPS)

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_HZ@{fg text}
                               lower Hertz-Limit: TotRow/TotClk-Changes,
                               which undergo this limit are ignored ¿.
                               DEFAULT: (MIN_HZ=)

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_HZ@{fg text}
                               upper Hertz-Limit: TotRow/TotClk-Changes,
                               which exceed this limit are ignored ¿.
                               DEFAULT: (MAX_HZ)

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_KHZ@{fg text}
                               lower Kilohertz-Limit: TotRow/TotClk-Changes,
                               which undergo this limit are ignored ¿.
                               DEFAULT: (MIN_KHZ)

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_KHZ@{fg text}
                               upper Kilohertz-Limit: TotRow/TotClk-Changes,
                               which exceed this limit are ignored ¿.
                               DEFAULT: (MAX_KHZ)

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_HB@{fg text}
                               lower limit of HBStrt/HBStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 0

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_HB@{fg text}
                               upper limit of HBStrt/HBStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 63

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_HS@{fg text}
                               lower limit of HSStrt/HSStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 0

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_HS@{fg text}
                               upper limit of HSStrt/HSStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 63

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_VB@{fg text}
                               lower limit of VBStrt/VBStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 0

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_VB@{fg text}
                               upper limit of VBStrt/VBStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 7999

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_VS@{fg text}
                               lower limit of VSStrt/VSStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 0

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_VS@{fg text}
                               upper limit of VSStrt/VSStop sliders
                               DEFAULT: 7999

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_TOTROW@{fg text}
                               lower limit of TotRow slider
                               DEFAULT: 0

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_TOTROW@{fg text}
                               upper limit of TotRow slider
                               DEFAULT: 1535

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_TOTCLK@{fg text}
                               lower limit of TotClk slider
                               DEFAULT: 0

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_TOTCLK@{fg text}
                               upper limit of TotClk slider
                               DEFAULT: 767

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_DIM@{fg text}
                               lower limit of Overscan sliders
                               DEFAULT: -127

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_DIM@{fg text}
                               upper limit of Overscan sliders
                               DEFAULT: 2047

    ñ @{fg shine}MIN_VIEW@{fg text}
                               lower limit of VPRMinX, VPRMaxX, VPRMinY,
                               VPRMaxY, VPosX, VPosY, MinCol and MinRow sliders
                               DEFAULT: -127

    ñ @{fg shine}MAX_VIEW@{fg text}
                               upper limit of VPRMinX, VPRMaxX, VPRMinY,
                               VPRMaxY, VPosX, VPosY, MinCol and MinRow sliders
                               DEFAULT: 2047

    ñ @{fg shine}LEAVESCREENREQ@{fg text}
                               when you want to leave an 'editable' (Amiga-)Screen,
                               and have this ToolType set, the program asks you,
                               if your settings are to be saved or ignored.
                               DEFAULT: (LEAVESCREENREQ)

    ñ @{fg shine}CUSTOMSCRMINWIDTH@{fg text}
                               your defined private Screen have this minimum width
                               regardless of that what you define in the asl requester
                               This could be useful for very small screenmodes or
                               exotic font settings or when you have no virtual groups
                               defined.
                               DEFAULT: 640

    ñ @{fg shine}CUSTOMSCRMINHEIGHT@{fg text}
                               the same for the height.
                               DEFAULT: 480

    ñ @{fg shine}SMREQ_HEIGHT@{fg text}
                               height of screenmoderequester
                               DEFAULT: 400

    ñ @{fg shine}CUSTOMSCRDEPTH@{fg text}
                               default value for the screen depth. This is useful,
                               if you have some patterns for your MUI-windows defined
                               DEFAULT: 4


    ¿ = if the starts on a screen, whose frequencies are already out of range,
        the ranges will be ignored until you change the screen. if the other
        screen matches the limits then thy will be respected again.
@endnode

@node "SavedToolTypes" "Saved ToolTypes"

    @{b}TOOLTYPES OF THE MONITOR FILES@{ub}

    Some settings are saved only once per monitor file.
    They are:

    ñ @{fg shine}TOTCLKS=0x<Hex>@{fg text}            total colorclocks
    ñ @{fg shine}TOTROWS=0x<Hex>@{fg text}            totale rows

    ñ @{fg shine}MINROW=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             minimum displayed row
    ñ @{fg shine}MINCOL=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             minimum displayed column
    ñ @{fg shine}MAXCOL=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             hmmm...

    ñ @{fg shine}BEAMCON0=0x<Hex>@{fg text}           Beamcon0 flags

    ñ @{fg shine}HBSTRT=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             horizontal blank start (>0 !!!)
    ñ @{fg shine}HBSTOP=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             horizontal blank stop
    ñ @{fg shine}HSSTRT=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             horizontal sync start
    ñ @{fg shine}HSSTOP=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             horizontal sync stop
    ñ @{fg shine}VBSTRT=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             vertikal blank start
    ñ @{fg shine}VBSTOP=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             vertikal blank stop
    ñ @{fg shine}VSSTRT=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             vertikal sync start
    ñ @{fg shine}VSSTOP=0x<Hex>@{fg text}             vertikal sync stop

    ñ @{fg shine}REFMODEID=0x<HexID>@{fg text}        standard Amiga ModeID, the following overscan
                                 settings are dependent on this ModeID
    ñ @{fg shine}NOMMINX=<Integer>@{fg text}          minimum nominal overscan x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}NOMMAXX=<Integer>@{fg text}          maximum nominal overscan x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}NOMMINY=<Integer>@{fg text}          minimum nominal overscan y-value
    ñ @{fg shine}NOMMAXY=<Integer>@{fg text}          maximum nominal overscan y-value

    ñ @{fg shine}MAXMINX=<Integer>@{fg text}          minimum maximal overscan x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}MAXMAXX=<Integer>@{fg text}          maximum maximal overscan x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}MAXMINY=<Integer>@{fg text}          minimum maximal overscan y-value
    ñ @{fg shine}MAXMAXY=<Integer>@{fg text}          maximum maximal overscan y-value

    ñ @{fg shine}VIDEOMINX=<Integer>@{fg text}        minimum video overscan x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}VIDEOMAXX=<Integer>@{fg text}        maximum video overscan x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}VIDEOMINY=<Integer>@{fg text}        minimum video overscan y-value
    ñ @{fg shine}VIDEOMAXY=<Integer>@{fg text}        maximum video overscan y-value

    Other settings are saved for every different ModeID:

    ñ @{fg shine}MODEID0=0x<Hex>@{fg text}            reference mode for the following settings
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMINX0=<Integer>@{fg text}         minimum ViewPositionRange x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMAXX0=<Integer>@{fg text}         maximum ViewPositionRange x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMINY0=<Integer>@{fg text}         minimum ViewPositionRange y-value
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMAXY0=<Integer>@{fg text}         maximum ViewPositionRange y-value

    ñ @{fg shine}VPOSX0=<Integer>@{fg text}           ViewPosition x-value
    ñ @{fg shine}VPOSY0=<Integer>@{fg text}           ViewPosition y-value

    ñ @{fg shine}MODENAME0=<String>@{fg text}         ModeName (max. 31 chars)

    ñ @{fg shine}PROPERTIES0=0x<Hex>@{fg text}        Interlace a.s.o.


    ñ @{fg shine}MODEID1=0x<Hex>@{fg text}            next ModeID
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMINX1=<Integer>@{fg text}
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMAXX1=<Integer>@{fg text}
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMINY1=<Integer>@{fg text}
    ñ @{fg shine}VPRMAXY1=<Integer>@{fg text}
    ñ @{fg shine}VPOSX1=<Integer>@{fg text}
    ñ @{fg shine}VPOSY1=<Integer>@{fg text}
    ñ @{fg shine}MODENAME1=<String>@{fg text}
    ñ @{fg shine}PROPERTIES1=0x<Hex>@{fg text}


    ñ @{fg shine}MODEID2=0x<Hex>@{fg text}
    (...)


    Contrary to previous versions the overscan settings are saved only once for
    a reference ModeID. Overscan values for the other ModeIDs are
    algorhythmically calculated according to pixel clock, interlace/scandbl.
@endnode

@node "Monitordrivers" "Monitordrivers"

    @{b}MONITORDRIVERS@{ub}

    Please use the monitor drivers of the WB 3.1.
@endnode

@node "HighGfx" " "

    @{b}HIGHGFX@{ub}

    If the @{b}@{fg shine}PROTO_MONITOR_ID@{ub}@{fg text} (0x51000) was found,
    the monitor shown is "@{b}HighGFX@{ub}".
@endnode

@node "MIPrefs" "MIPrefs"

    @{b}M_IPREFS@{ub}

    This program (must be in this archive) is best to be called in @{b}s:user-startup@{ub}.
    It reads all @{b}icons@{ub} in the directory @{b}DEVS:Monitors/@{ub}.
    The found ToolTypes will be evaluated and the monitor settings will be changed.
    Please read also the separate manual for "M_IPrefs".
@endnode

@node "Localizing" " "

    @{b}LOCALIZING@{ub}

    @{b}MonSpecsMUI@{ub} supports the @{b}locale.library@{ub}.
    With the help of the file @{b}MonSpecsMUI.cd@{ub}, which is included,
    you can create your own catalogs if @{b}your language@{ub} is not included.
    As an @{b}example@{ub} there is the @{b}german@{ub} version of the file @{b}MonSpecsMUI.ct@{ub}.
@endnode

