@node "Installation" "Installation"

    @{b}INSTALLATION@{ub}

    Installation is simple.
    Drag the @{b}program@{ub} with its @{b}icon@{ub} to a @{b}directory of your choice@{ub}.
    Drag the @{b}catalog@{ub} in directory @{b}"LOCALE:<speech>/"@{ub}.
    Drag @{b}MIPrefs@{ub} somewhere in the command path (e.g.: @{b}"C:"@{ub}).
    Call @{b}MIPrefs@{ub} in @{b}s:user-startup@{ub}.

    @{i}Normal Call:@{ui}
    MIPrefs                 ; user-startup

    @{i}If you find, that your settings are not respected:@{ui}
    MIPrefs                 ; user-startup
    SYS:Prefs/Overscan USE  ; user-startup

    This might help for the monitordriver "Multiscan" of WB 3.1.

    Ready.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

    @{b}USAGE@{ub}

    Right at the top left in the window you find
        ñ Name of monitor
        ñ Name of Screenmode
        ñ ModeID

    Right beside it you can change the screen to either an existing public
    or a self-defined new private screen. I think there is no need to
    create your own public screens.

    In the left area under it there is an information area for some frequencies and
    timings (e.g. duration of a single scanline)

    Let's come to the right area of the window.
    There is a big register gadget with 6 pages:

        @{b}ñ ModeName@{ub}

          Here you can edit the name of the screenmode.

        @{b}ñ Monitor@{ub}

          Here you can edit blanks/syncs and the amount of colorclocks/rows.

        @{b}ñ Overscan@{ub}

          Here can you edit the overscans which are not editable by Prefs/Overscan.

        @{b}ñ View@{ub}

          Try it out !

        @{b}ñ BeamCon0@{ub}

          Here you can set or clear the flags for the BeamCon0 tooltype
          of the monitordriver icon.

          Example:

          Go in PAL mode.
          Clear the PAL flag.
          Press the 'LoadView()' button below.
          Your display should now be NTSC.

          @{b}!!! BE CAREFUL WITH THESE FLAGS !!!@{ub}

          The functions below are embedded in the structure @{b}MonitorSpec@{ub}.

          The @{b}KillView()@{ub}-function is as far as i know only implemented in
          the monitordriver @{b}A2024@{ub}.
          The @{b}MrgCop()@{ub}-function crashes everytime i call them.
          You can not call this function,
          instead you will be given a @{b}DisplayBeep()@{ub}

        @{b}ñ Props@{ub}

          Here you can set or clear the property flags of a screenmode

    At the bottom in the window there are five more gadgets:

        @{b}ñ Save & End@{ub}
          Save all, then end

        @{b}ñ Save Only@{ub}
          Save all

        @{b}ñ Use & End@{ub}
          Use (no action), then end

        @{b}ñ Reset All@{ub}
          Reset all (see also tooltype "QUICKRESET")

        @{b}ñ Cancel@{ub}
          Reset all, then end
@endnode

@node "Changes" "Changes"

    @{b}CHANGES@{ub}

    @{b}Changes for 40.375 after 40.356:@{ub}
    - internal optimizations
    - no senseless flickering anymore (do_monitor())
    - new Tooltype: HOLD - Settings which are made in simulate mode are taken
      over to normal program runnng. This can be useful if you want to change
      more than one setting at once.
    - new save Tooltype: MAXCOL. Cause there's MINCOL, there will be MAXCOL...
    - change screen text gadgets are now ghosted if there's no text in them
    - MINROW / MINCOL went from 'View' to 'Monitor' page
@endnode

